00:01:16.229 --> 00:01:22.310
What you just saw was groundbreaking director
Alfred Hitchcock discussing the power of the

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:26.659
montage to influence, even change a viewer’s
opinion.

00:01:26.659 --> 00:01:29.390
This is known as the Kuleshov effect.

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:40.109
Soviet filmmaker Lev Kuleshov showed the following
clip to an audience.

00:01:40.109 --> 00:01:46.259
Then he showed them this clip.

00:01:46.259 --> 00:01:56.379
Finally, this.

00:01:56.379 --> 00:02:01.509
The audience fervently remarked how the expression
on the man’s face was different in all three

00:02:01.509 --> 00:02:08.759
sequences, one showed hunger, the next sadness
and finally lust, as though they were all

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:12.000
shot independently.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.840
This was not the case, the only difference
between the three shots is the image spliced

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.280
in between the closeup.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:26.150
Across all three examples, the closeup shot
itself was the exact same piece of film, the

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:28.739
man’s expression did not change.

00:02:28.739 --> 00:02:33.950
Kuleshov used this experiment to demonstrate
how the considered assemblance of completely

00:02:33.950 --> 00:02:42.590
unrelated pieces of film and images, can significantly
alter a viewer’s emotional response.

00:02:42.590 --> 00:02:50.239
This simple yet powerful technique has been
used in propaganda, to wage wars, win wars,

00:02:50.239 --> 00:02:53.220
spread tyranny and keep it at bay.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:59.569
It has been used in humanity’s greatest
films to make audiences laugh, sob and scared

00:02:59.569 --> 00:03:00.569
senseless.

00:03:00.569 --> 00:03:05.780
But there is one force in our modern world
that holds the deftest hand, the slimiest

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:12.379
skill, the most astute ability to rearrange
information, to influence nations, change

00:03:12.379 --> 00:03:16.860
narratives and breed mass contempt.

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:18.389
The media.

00:03:18.389 --> 00:03:26.159
The ability of the press, TV news and increasingly
digital media to take the truth and warp it

00:03:26.159 --> 00:03:30.550
to align with their ideological agenda is
unrivalled.

00:03:30.550 --> 00:03:35.500
Fastidiously straddling the legal boundaries
as they do so.

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:36.560
How you may ask?

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:39.950
I’m sure you’re all too aware of fake
news.

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:46.790
Well, I’m not talking about fake news, I
mean to draw your attention to a far more

00:03:46.790 --> 00:03:53.969
underhanded means of deception utilised by
what you may consider the “genuine” media.

00:03:53.969 --> 00:03:59.349
Like most people, you have probably long suspected
that the big six media giants that control

00:03:59.349 --> 00:04:05.579
traditional news or the new generation of
digital media haven’t always reported stories

00:04:05.579 --> 00:04:08.549
to you in the most genuine and factual way.

00:04:08.549 --> 00:04:15.060
But it’s likely that you’ve never quite
been able to put your finger on how or why.

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:20.680
This is because the techniques they use to
subvert the truth are crucially subtle.

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:27.160
They are required, even mandated by law, in
certain countries, to be subtle.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:32.820
So allow me to enlighten you with just a few
of the many masterfully subtle subversions

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:37.070
big media uses to sabotage the status quo.

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:38.630
The media loves statistics.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:39.630
Why?

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:46.610
It’s not because statistics offer absolute,
empirically factual truths in a concise and

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:51.150
easily digestible format, it’s quite the
opposite.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:55.770
The media loves statistics because they can
easily be modified to support the narrative

00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:58.110
they wish the current story to tell.

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:04.220
In 2005 the state of Florida introduced the
controversial “Stand Your Ground” law,

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:09.169
permitting people to use lethal force against
an attacker even if it would be possible to

00:05:09.169 --> 00:05:13.260
safely retreat from the situation.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:18.450
Reuters published the following chart showing
the number of gun deaths in Florida over time.

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:23.720
“Wow” you may remark, gun deaths dropped
drastically following the introduction of

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:26.900
Stand Your Ground in 2005.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:28.130
Wrong.

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:35.520
Notice the y-axis has been inverted so that
zero is at the top, ergo as the line-graph

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:41.229
flows down the chart, the number of gun deaths
increases.

00:05:41.229 --> 00:05:47.110
This is purposely opposed to the way in which
we have been normalised to expect the progression

00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:51.990
of data to invariably appear on an x/y-axis
chart.

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:57.419
We naturally expect up to mean more, not less.

00:05:57.419 --> 00:06:00.160
We also expect zero to be at the bottom-left
of charts.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:06.080
So then, at first glance, it would appear
that following the 2005 statute, Florida gun

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:10.530
deaths dropped to almost zero.

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:15.990
Another trick is truncating the y-axis.

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:20.630
The news loves to use this tactic with crime
statistics to make them sound more rapturously

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:22.140
apocalyptic.

00:06:22.140 --> 00:06:27.519
How many times have you read or heard news
similar to this “murder rates up 100% on

00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:28.729
last year”.

00:06:28.729 --> 00:06:32.240
What they often fail to report are the actual
numbers.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.959
What if there was only one murder last year?

00:06:34.959 --> 00:06:41.050
If this year there are two murders, that is
indeed an increase of 100%.

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:48.120
But to the dismay of professional fearmongering
frauds, crime rates are usually extremely

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:51.940
low, to begin with, except in a few rare places
in the world.

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:58.409
Two murders in even a small city of say 200,000
people is not a statistic to give you cause

00:06:58.409 --> 00:07:03.280
to organise a sign-writing party with your
belligerent blue-haired buddies.

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:08.170
So when you’re shown a chart such as this
you would be forgiven for thinking that interest

00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:12.610
rates shot up drastically between 2008 and
2012.

00:07:12.610 --> 00:07:18.640
If this were true we would have started donating
our organs to pay our mortgages by now.

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:24.220
Notice how the y-axis is severely truncated
to exacerbate the most minute increments of

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:25.220
data.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:30.880
Plot the same data on a chart where the baseline
is set at zero and what we can now observe

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:35.460
is that interest rates, in fact, stayed staunchly
static.

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:39.680
It’s not always appropriate to start a y-axis
at zero.

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:45.190
Sometimes to demonstrate a huge shift in data
within a far greater range the y-axis must

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:46.269
be truncated.

00:07:46.269 --> 00:07:51.110
But always be aware when you suspect that
it has been done to mislead you.

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:56.060
As it has in an even more devious way in this
chart published by the Ministry of Health

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:58.280
for New South Wales in 2013.

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:04.050
What’s going on here is more subtle than
simply truncating an axis.

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:11.770
43,000 nurses are graphically represented
