00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:18.110
to do so.

00:16:18.110 --> 00:16:21.829
I’m sure you will have noticed these in
use on a daily basis anyway.

00:16:21.829 --> 00:16:27.770
So, for instance, anchors and presenters,
will often fall back on binary injunctions

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:34.649
such as “Yes or no”, “just answer the
question YES or NO” when the opponent gives

00:16:34.649 --> 00:16:39.720
a lengthy answer to a deeply nuanced question
that cannot possibly be answered with a simple

00:16:39.720 --> 00:16:43.860
yes or no, without coming across as a belligerent
fool.

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:50.059
When an opponent uses empirical evidence or
commonly known axioms to support their argument

00:16:50.059 --> 00:16:55.110
it is common for the interviewer to come back
with the ignorant response “well that’s

00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:56.459
your opinion”.

00:16:56.459 --> 00:17:01.749
This is commonly used when the interviewer
knows their opponent just made a substantial

00:17:01.749 --> 00:17:05.390
and valid point that they cannot intellectually
retort.

00:17:05.390 --> 00:17:11.470
So, by instead chalking it up as “their
opinion” it undermines the factual foundations

00:17:11.470 --> 00:17:15.180
of the entire argument that person just laid
down.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:20.709
When introducing a guest it is common for
a news anchor, talk show host or other journalists

00:17:20.709 --> 00:17:26.600
to preface the interview with something similar
to “John Smith claims he is an avian expert

00:17:26.600 --> 00:17:31.790
but his critics say he molests pigeons, let’s
find out”.

00:17:31.790 --> 00:17:36.170
Notice the critical syntax here “but his
critics say”.

00:17:36.170 --> 00:17:37.350
Which critics?

00:17:37.350 --> 00:17:43.850
It is very rare the critics who supposedly
said that are actually identified.

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:50.820
A broad generalisation such as this rarely
attracts calls for substantiation and it doesn’t

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:55.160
matter anyway, the damage has already been
done.

00:17:55.160 --> 00:18:01.700
In the eyes of most people watching, listening
or reading, Mr Smith is now a pigeon molester.

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:06.790
When in fact those “critics” could consist
of no more than the journalist who made that

00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:12.030
statement witnessing a homeless man shouting
“bloody pigeon molester” at Mr Smith as

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:14.679
he innocently walked down the street.

00:18:14.679 --> 00:18:21.149
It is then legally justified for such a conjecture
to exist, even if it does not represent greater

00:18:21.149 --> 00:18:23.570
public opinion.

00:18:23.570 --> 00:18:28.900
Subtle phrasing such as “but their critics
say” is necessary in a world with libel

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:35.330
and slander laws, because the journalist themselves
are not making the vilification, some mysterious

00:18:35.330 --> 00:18:36.530
critic is.

00:18:36.530 --> 00:18:42.669
I’ll let you into a little secret, almost
every time a journalist uses the phrasing

00:18:42.669 --> 00:18:49.390
“but his or her critics say” prepended
to a string of particularly incendiary pejoratives.

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:54.801
It is actually a means for the supposedly
“impartial” journalist to out their personal

00:18:54.801 --> 00:19:00.200
views or that of their company’s on the
character in question, without personally

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:02.360
risking legal defamation.

00:19:02.360 --> 00:19:09.080
An example can be seen here on torontolife.com
“When U of T professor Jordan Peterson pledged

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:14.409
never to use gender-neutral pronouns, he sparked
a vicious campus battle.

00:19:14.409 --> 00:19:19.830
The free-speech advocates say he’s combating
the tyranny of political correctness.

00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:29.490
His critics say he’s a privileged, trans-phobic
bigot who must be stopped”.

00:19:29.490 --> 00:19:42.620
Also, if a journalist uses the word “allegedly”
before a statement, then it’s usually the

00:19:42.620 --> 00:19:47.950
same damn thing, it’s just another way to
say “their critics say”.

00:19:47.950 --> 00:19:52.850
Subtle linguistic tricks such as this that
cunningly transmute opinions into facts are

00:19:52.850 --> 00:19:57.830
especially important and thus often utilised
in British news.

00:19:57.830 --> 00:20:03.350
In the UK impartiality laws exist under the
Communications Act of 2003 that legally mandates

00:20:03.350 --> 00:20:09.700
news in any form to exercise “due impartiality
and due accuracy”.

